I am working on extending a concrete (but derived) C++ class in python, and then calling the overridden function in a C++ thread (via an async).  I call the function ``added_fcn`` in the C++ level, which calls the python implementation, and then it just gets stuck (hangs) and never returns a value.  In the debugger, I can see it is in the wait function, and never leaves.

For what it's worth, originally I had hoped to just pass a std::function to my class, but it suffers from the same hanging behavior as extending a class.  Calling the function, or the overloaded method (not from a thread), works totally fine.

OSX, Xcode, python 2.7

#### Reproducible example code

interface_pybind11.cxx
``` c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
#include <pybind11/operators.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

class A{
public:
    virtual void pure_virt() = 0;
};

class B : public A{
public:
    void pure_virt() override {

    };
    virtual int added_fcn(){
        return -1;
    }
};

class PyB : public B {
    public:
        /* Inherit the constructors */
        using B::B;

        /* Trampoline (need one for each virtual function) */
        int added_fcn() override {
            PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(
                int,                      /* Return type */
                B,            /* Parent class */
                added_fcn,                   /* Name of function in C++ (must match Python name) */
                                            /* Argument(s) */
            );
        }
};

void call_parallel(const std::shared_ptr<B> &BB) {
    // This function hangs
    std::future<void> f2 = std::async(std::launch::async, [BB](){ BB->added_fcn() ; }); 
    f2.wait();
}

void init_fitter(py::module &m){

    py::class_<A>(m, "A");

    py::class_<B, PyB, A, std::shared_ptr<B> >(m, "B")
        .def(py::init<>())
        .def("added_fcn", &B::added_fcn);

    m.def("call_parallel", call_parallel);
}

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(PolyFitter) {
    py::module m("PolyFitter", "PolyFitter module");
    init_fitter(m);
    return m.ptr();
}
```

test.py
``` python
    import sys; sys.path.append('build/pybind11/Debug')
    import PolyFitter as pf
    class B(pf.B):
        def __init__(self):
            super(B, self).__init__()
            pass

        def added_fcn(self):
            return 3

    b = B()
    pf.call_parallel(b)
```

Best illustrated by an example:

```cpp
// default r/v policy = reference_internal 
py::make_iterator(begin, end);

// this one's still using reference_internal due to iterator type caching
py::make_iterator(begin, end, py::return_value_policy::copy);
```

This would be due to handle caster being created just once:  https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/blob/master/include/pybind11/pybind11.h#L1140 -- which makes all subsequent calls effectively ignore the `Extra...` arguments. Doesn't looks like it's by design? I actually have a use case where I need to select between copy/ref versions of iterator at runtime...

// One other very minor thing, it would be a tad nicer to have `class_<state>(handle(), "iterator")` instead of `class_<state>(handle(), "")` since the iterators appear as `< at 0x12312312>` in Python; same with `key_iterator`.

Hey guys, 

I was trying out your example in the ReadMe but I can't seem to get it to work. I tried fixing this myself I know my readme examples might not work often times. I had a look at your implementation, and I found an issue in the _load_geometry() function. (I'm guessing from probably a change on shapely's end) 

The load_wkb() and load_wkt() functions don't throw an actual exception when they die, at least in my implementation of shapely, so this try/except code block currently doesn't work  as its probably intended anymore. You could probably make an inferences off a stringified block of geometry (i.e. if it contains '/' ) and fix it pretty easily. 

```python 
    def _load_geometry(self, geometry_spec):
        if isinstance(geometry_spec, BaseGeometry):
            return geometry_spec

        try:
            return load_wkb(geometry_spec)
        except:
            try:
                return load_wkt(geometry_spec)
            except:
                return None
```

